# OTMS Infrastructure Provisioning & Instance Type Comparison

## Overview
This document compares manually provisioned infrastructure vs Auto Scaling Group (ASG) provisioning for OTMS and provides Graviton, AMD and Intel instance recommendations to support performance, scalability, cost optimization and maintainability.

---

# Objectives

- Identify components provisioned manually vs through ASGs  
- Compare Graviton, AMD and Intel instances  
- Recommend best instance types for OTMS components  
- Reduce future scaling and maintenance risks  

---

# Infrastructure Provisioning Comparison

| Component | Provisioning Model | Reason |
|----------|-------------------|--------|
| Frontend / NGINX | ASG | Stateless and scalable |
| Application APIs | ASG | High availability and auto scaling |
| Worker Services | ASG | Elastic workloads |
| Redis | Manual | Stateful |
| Kafka | Manual | Cluster-sensitive |
| Elasticsearch | Manual | Stateful |
| PostgreSQL | Manual | Persistent workload |
| MongoDB | Manual | Persistent workload |
| ScyllaDB | Manual | Persistent workload |
| Bastion | Manual | Security controlled |
| Jenkins | Manual | Persistent configuration |

---

# Manual vs ASG Comparison

| Criteria | Manual | ASG |
|---------|--------|-----|
| Scaling | Manual | Automatic |
| High Availability | Medium | High |
| Self Healing | No | Yes |
| Operational Overhead | High | Lower |
| Best For | Stateful | Stateless |

---

# Recommended Provisioning Strategy

## ASG Based Components
```text
Frontend
Application APIs
Worker Services
```

Suggested ASG:
```text
Min:1
Desired:2
Max:4
```

---

## Manual Provisioned Components
```text
Databases
Redis
Kafka
Elasticsearch
Bastion
Jenkins
```

